A?    The effective date and time;

A?    The place of use;

A?    The hours during which the source of ignition may be used, not to exceed 24 hours;

A?    The specific location or piece of equipment where the source of ignition will be used; 

A?    The nature of the use of the source of ignition; and,

A?    Any special precautions or limitations to be observed before, during, or after the use of the source of ignition, including the need for a fire watch and fire hoses or extinguishers.  The criteria for needing a fire watch and the responsibilities of the fire watch are identified in the fire prevention and suppression procedure.

Safety (including hot work) permits are issued at the job site.  The issuer of the permit performs an inspection of the area to ensure the following prior to authorization of the hot work permit:

A?    The source of ignition may be safely used A? The fire prevention and suppression procedure requires that only approved apparatus be used and that personnel performing the hot work (including contractors) be informed of the hazards and properly trained.  Also, the flammable gas or vapor content in the air must be less than 1% of the lowest content that is flammable or explosive; 

A?    Combustible materials (including oil accumulations) in areas that will be exposed during hot work are protected or relocated;

A?    Proper fire extinguishing equipment is available to employees performing the hot work.

Personnel in the immediate work area are notified prior to initiation of the hot work to make them aware of the ignition source.  This awareness allows applicable personnel to quickly contact the fire watch and personnel performing hot work when continued use of the source of ignition becomes hazardous.   Safe access and egress is also discussed.  

